<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-707-830  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 707 830.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics Weekly  July 4 1990 n1515 p12(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Memory man. (Dr. Tsugio Makimoto, director and general manager ofHitachi's Semiconductor Design and Development Center)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Manners, David.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Tsugio Makimoto, director of Hitachi's Semiconductor Research andDevelopment Center, considers the 1990s as the decade of thetransition from megabytes to gigabytes.andP;  He sees the next tenyears as the decade of the sub-micron.andP;  Makimoto demonstrates hisinterest in cooperative research and development through consortiasuch as SEMATECH (US), JESSI (Europe) and Sortec (Japan).andP;  He alsospeaks about Hitachi's progress in telecommunications, withparticular emphasis on the development of a portable speechtranslating machine, pointing out unresolved difficulties in voicerecognition and the possibility of a telephone automatictranslation system.andP;  Makimoto answers questions related toHitachi's development of complementary metal oxide semiconductors(CMOS) and more recent research in high speed bipolar CMOS,advances which have placed Hitachi ahead of other firms in thefields of dynamic and static RAM.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Hitachi Ltd. (officials and employees).andO;Topic:     Industry AnalysisSemiconductor IndustryMicroprocessorsTrendsFuture TechnologiesResearch and Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Tsugio Makimoto. (portrait)Person:    Makimoto, Tsugio (interviews).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>